'''Bille August''' (born 9 November 1948) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[Academy Award]]-winning [[film]] and [[television]] [[film director|director]]. His film ''[[Pelle the Conqueror]]'' from 1987 won the [[Palme D'or]], [[Academy Award]] and [[Golden Globe]]. He is one of only six directors to win the [[Palme D'or]] twice, winning the prestigious award again in 1992 for ''[[The Best Intentions]]'', based on the autobiographical script by [[Ingmar Bergman]]. He was married to Swedish actress [[Pernilla August]] from 1991 to 1997. His son [[Anders August]] is a screenwriter.

==Career==
On 23 September 2011, Bille August announced that he has opened his studio in [[Hangzhou]], [[China]] and taken a position as Tianpeng Media's Art Director, aiming to produce Chinese films for Tianpeng Media over the next few years. Tianpeng Media is a new media company established in 2010. The company so far has produced two films, ''The Women Knight of Mirror'' (竞雄女侠秋瑾) and ''The Years of Qi Xiao Fu'' (七小福之燃情岁月), which will be released later this year. Bille is the first foreign director to be hired by the Chinese film company. Recently, August also accepted the invitation from the Hangzhou government to serve as a "culture consultant" for the city.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://asiapacificarts.usc.edu/article@apa?academy_award-winning_director_bille_august_opens_his_studio_in_hangzhou_17467.aspx | title = Academy Award-winning director Bille August opens his studio in Hangzhou | publisher = Asia Pacific arts | date = 10/04/2011}}</ref>

His 2013 film ''[[Night Train to Lisbon (film)|Night Train to Lisbon]]'' premiered out of competition at the [[63rd Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name="Berlin">{{Cite web|url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/presse/pressemitteilungen/alle/Alle-Detail_16724.html |title=Berlinale 2013: Competition Now Complete |accessdate=2013-01-25 |work=berlinale}}</ref>

==Selected filmography==
* ''[[In My Life (1978 film)|Honning måne]]'' (1978, In My Life)
** Entered into the [[11th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name="Moscow1979">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1979 |title=11th Moscow International Film Festival (1979) |accessdate=2013-01-18 |work=MIFF}}</ref>
* ''Verden er så stor, så stor'' (1980)
** TV Movie
* ''[[Maj (1982 film)|Maj]]'' (1982)
** TV Movie
* ''[[Zappa (film)|Zappa]]'' (1983)
** based on the book by Danish writer [[Bjarne Reuter]]. Screened at the [[1983 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name="festival-cannes.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/1538/year/1983.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Zappa |accessdate=2009-06-20|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and the [[13th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name="Moscow1983">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1983 |title=13th Moscow International Film Festival (1983) |accessdate=2013-01-31 |work=MIFF}}</ref>
* ''[[Busters verden]]'' (1984, Buster's world)
** based on the book by Danish writer [[Bjarne Reuter]]
* ''[[Twist and Shout (film)|Tro, håb og kærlighed]]'' (1984, Twist and Shout). Entered into the [[14th Moscow International Film Festival]].<ref name="Moscow1985">{{cite web |url=http://www.moscowfilmfestival.ru/miff34/eng/archives/?year=1985 |title=14th Moscow International Film Festival (1985) |accessdate=2013-02-08 |work=MIFF}}</ref>
** sequel to ''Zappa''
* ''[[Pelle the Conqueror|Pelle Erobreren]]'' (1987, Pelle the Conqueror)
** based on a novel by Danish author [[Martin Andersen Nexø]]
** won the [[Golden Palm]] at the [[1988 Cannes Film Festival]]<ref name="cannes-1988.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/299/year/1988.html |title=Festival de Cannes: Pelle the Conqueror |accessdate=2009-07-27|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref> and an [[Academy Award for Best Foreign Language Film]]
* ''[[Den goda viljan]]'' (1991, The Best Intentions)
** script by [[Ingmar Bergman]].
** won the [[Golden Palm]] at the [[1992 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name="cannes-1992.com">{{cite web |url=http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/archives/ficheFilm/id/12/year/1992.html |title=Festival de Cannes: The Best Intentions |accessdate=2009-08-14|work=festival-cannes.com}}</ref>
* ''[[The House of the Spirits (film)|The House of the Spirits]]'' (1993)
** based on a novel by [[Chile]]an author [[Isabel Allende]].
* ''[[The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles]]'' (1993) Two episodes
** Vienna, November 1908 (Season 2, Episode 9)
** Northern Italy, June 1918 (Season 2, Episode 10)
* ''[[Jerusalem (1996 film)|Jerusalem]]'' (1996)
** based on a novel by the Swedish author [[Selma Lagerlöf]].
* ''[[Smilla's Sense of Snow (film)|Smilla's Sense of Snow]]'' (1997)
** based on the novel [[Miss Smilla's Feeling for Snow]] by Danish author [[Peter Høeg]].
** nominated for the [[Golden Bear]] at [[47th Berlin International Film Festival|Berlin]]<ref name="Berlinale">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1997/02_programm_1997/02_Programm_1997.html |title=Berlinale: 1997 Programme |accessdate=2012-01-12 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>
* ''[[Les Misérables (1998 film)|Les Misérables]]'' (1998)
** based on [[Les Misérables|the novel of the same name]] by French author [[Victor Hugo]].
* ''[[En sang for Martin]]'' (2001, A Song for Martin)
* ''[[Return to Sender (film)|Return to Sender]]'' (2005)
* ''[[Goodbye Bafana]]'' (2007)
** won the ''[[Cinema for Peace]] 2007 Best Director Award''
* ''[[The Passion of Marie]]'' (2012)
* ''[[Night Train to Lisbon (film)|Night Train to Lisbon]]'' (2013)

